110    /**
111    * <p>
112    * An operator accepts an array of input objects and generates an array of output objects that can
113    * be processed by other operators. Both must implement the IOObject interface. This is the
114    * superclass which must be extended by all RapidMiner operators. Please refer to the RapidMiner
115    * tutorial for a detailed description how to implement your operator.
116    * </p>
117    *
118    * <p>
119    * As default, operators consume their input by using it. This is often a useful behavior especially
120    * in complex processes. For example, a learning operator consumes an example set to produce a model
121    * and so does a cross validation to produce a performance value of the learning method. To receive
122    * the input {@link IOObject} of a certain class simply use {@link #getInput(Class class)}. This
123    * method delivers the first object of the desired class which is in the input of this operator. The
124    * delivered object is consumed afterwards and thus is removed from input. If the operator alters
125    * this object, it should return the altered object as output again. Therefore, you have to add the
126    * object to the output array which is delivered by the {@link #apply()} method of the operator. You
127    * also have to declare it in {@link #getOutputClasses()}. All input objects which are not used by
128    * your operator will be automatically passed to the next operators.
129    * </p>
130    *
131    * <p>
132    * In some cases it would be useful if the user can define if the input object should be consumed or
133    * not. For example, a validation chain like cross validation should estimate the performance but
134    * should also be able to return the example set which is then used to learn the overall model.
135    * Operators can change the default behavior for input consumption and a parameter will be
136    * automatically defined and queried. The default behavior is defined in the method
137    * {@link #getInputDescription(Class cls)} and should be overridden in these cases. Please note that
138    * input objects with a changed input description must not be defined in {@link #getOutputClasses()}
139    * and must not be returned at the end of apply. Both is automatically done with respect to the
140    * value of the automatically created parameter. Please refer to the Javadoc comments of this method
141    * for further explanations.
142    * </p>
143    *
144    * @see com.rapidminer.operator.OperatorChain
145    *
146    * @author Ralf Klinkenberg, Ingo Mierswa, Simon Fischer, Marius Helf
147    */
 
- Uncovered Elements: 0 (0) Complexity: 0 Complexity Density: -

- Uncovered Elements: 0 (0) Complexity: 1 Complexity Density: -
1620    private String replaceMacros(String value, String parameterKey) throws UndefinedParameterError {...
1621    if (value == null || getProcess() == null) {
1622    return value;
1623    }
1624    String returnValue = value;
1625    try {
1626    ParameterType parameterType = getParameters().getParameterType(parameterKey);
1627    if (parameterType == null) {

1632    returnValue = parameterType.substitutePredefinedMacros(returnValue, this);

1640    }
1641    } catch (RuntimeException e) {

1643    throw e;
1644    }
1645    return returnValue;
1646    }
